            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <title>Observations: Determinants</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        We defined <m>\text{det}(A)</m> for a <m>2 \times 2</m> matrix, but we could do this similarly 
                            for an <m>n \times n</m> matrix. For example, we could define it as the volume created by positively
                            oriented vectors in three dimensions. However, we'll develop other ways for computing the determinant
                            that are better suited for high dimensions.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        For an <m>n \times n</m> triangular matrix <m>T</m>, <m>\text{det}(T)</m> is just the
                                        product of its diagonal entries.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        If <m>\text{det}(A) \lt 0</m>, this tells us that <m>A</m> (as a matrix transformation) reverses
                                        the spatial orientation.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Viewing matrices as transformations, we see that <m>A</m> scales areas by the value 
                                        <m>\text{det}(A)</m>, <m>B</m> scales areas by the value <m>\text{det}(B)</m>, and <m>AB</m> 
                                        scales areas by <m>\text{det}(A) \times \text{det}(B)</m> (when viewed as composition), but also by
                                        <m>\text{det}(AB)</m> (when viewed as a single matrix). This implies
                                        <me>
                                            \text{det}(AB) = \text{det}(A) \cdot \text{det}(B)
                                        </me>.
                                        
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>

